1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,490
Let's start with one classification example.

2

00:00:02,490  -->  00:00:04,130
Let's say we are the admissions office at

3

00:00:04,130  -->  00:00:07,130
a university and our job is to accept or reject students.

4

00:00:07,130  -->  00:00:08,790
In order to evaluate students,

5

00:00:08,790  -->  00:00:10,270
we have two pieces of information,

6

00:00:10,270  -->  00:00:13,990
the results of a test and their grades in school.

7

00:00:13,990  -->  00:00:16,870
Let's take a look at some sample students.

8

00:00:16,870  -->  00:00:21,790
We'll start with student 1 who got 9/10 in the test and 8/10 in the grades.

9

00:00:21,790  -->  00:00:24,490
That student did quite well and got accepted.

10

00:00:24,490  -->  00:00:29,510
Then we have student 2 who got 3/10 in the test and 4/10 in the grades,

11

00:00:29,510  -->  00:00:31,690
and that student got rejected.

12

00:00:31,690  -->  00:00:36,890
Now we have a new student 3 who got 7/10 in the test and 6/10 in the grades,

13

00:00:36,890  -->  00:00:40,275
and we're wondering if the student gets accepted or not.

14

00:00:40,275  -->  00:00:44,560
Our first way to find this out is to plot students in a graph with

15

00:00:44,560  -->  00:00:47,080
the horizontal axis corresponding to the score and

16

00:00:47,080  -->  00:00:50,940
the test and the vertical axis corresponding to the grades,

17

00:00:50,940  -->  00:00:52,940
and the students would fit here.

18

00:00:52,940  -->  00:00:58,160
The students who got three and four gets located in the point that coordinates 3, 4,

19

00:00:58,160  -->  00:01:04,630
and the student who got nine and eight gets located in the point which coordinates 9,8.

20

00:01:04,630  -->  00:01:07,630
Now we'll do what we do in most of our algorithms,

21

00:01:07,630  -->  00:01:09,650
which is to look at the previous data.

22

00:01:09,650  -->  00:01:11,870
This is how the previous data looks.

23

00:01:11,870  -->  00:01:15,090
These are all the previous students that got accepted or rejected.

24

00:01:15,090  -->  00:01:17,130
The blue points correspond to students that got

25

00:01:17,130  -->  00:01:20,750
accepted and the red points to students that got rejected.

26

00:01:20,750  -->  00:01:23,150
We can see in this diagram that the students who

27

00:01:23,150  -->  00:01:25,130
did well in the test and grades are more likely to

28

00:01:25,130  -->  00:01:29,530
get accepted and the students who did poorly on both are more likely to get rejected.

29

00:01:29,530  -->  00:01:31,230
Let's start with a quiz.

30

00:01:31,230  -->  00:01:34,910
The quiz says, does the student 3 get accepted or rejected.

31

00:01:34,910  -->  00:01:38,510
What do you think? Enter your answer below.
